{"parse":{"title":"Li Tieguai","pageid":220758,"revid":829565822,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox\" style=\"width:22em\"><tbody><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n</td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size: 125%; background-color: #b0c4de;\">\n<b>Li Tieguai</b></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Li_Tieguai_under_a_Pine,_Ming_dynasty.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Li Tieguai under a Pine, Ming dynasty.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f7/Li_Tieguai_under_a_Pine%2C_Ming_dynasty.jpg/220px-Li_Tieguai_under_a_Pine%2C_Ming_dynasty.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"355\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f7/Li_Tieguai_under_a_Pine%2C_Ming_dynasty.jpg/330px-Li_Tieguai_under_a_Pine%2C_Ming_dynasty.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f7/Li_Tieguai_under_a_Pine%2C_Ming_dynasty.jpg/440px-Li_Tieguai_under_a_Pine%2C_Ming_dynasty.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1360\" data-file-height=\"2192\" /></a><div>The painting <i>Li Tieguai under a Pine</i>, Ming dynasty</div></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight:normal;\"><a href=\"/wiki/Traditional_Chinese_characters\" title=\"Traditional Chinese characters\">Traditional&#160;Chinese</a></th><td>\n<span style=\"font-size: 1rem\"><span lang=\"zh-Hant\" title=\"Chinese language text\">\u674e\u9435\u62d0</span></span></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight:normal;\"><a href=\"/wiki/Simplified_Chinese_characters\" title=\"Simplified Chinese characters\">Simplified Chinese</a></th><td>\n<span style=\"font-size: 1rem\"><span lang=\"zh-Hans\" title=\"Chinese language text\">\u674e\u94c1\u62d0</span></span></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<table class=\"collapsible collapsed\" style=\"padding:0;border:none;margin:-3px;width:auto;min-width:100%;font-size:100%;clear:none;float:none;background-color:transparent\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold;font-size: 100%; text-align: left; background-color: #f9ffbc;\">Transcriptions</th></tr><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;background-color: #dcffc9;\"><a href=\"/wiki/Standard_Chinese\" title=\"Standard Chinese\">Standard Mandarin</a></th></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight:normal;\"><a href=\"/wiki/Hanyu_Pinyin\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Hanyu Pinyin\">Hanyu Pinyin</a></th><td>\nL\u01d0 Ti\u011bgu\u01cei</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight:normal;\"><a href=\"/wiki/Wade%E2%80%93Giles\" title=\"Wade\u2013Giles\">Wade\u2013Giles</a></th><td>\nLi T'ieh-kuai</td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr style=\"display:none\"><td colspan=\"2\">\n</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><b>Li Tieguai</b> (lit. \"Iron Crutch Li\") is a <a href=\"/wiki/Chinese_mythology\" title=\"Chinese mythology\">Chinese mythological</a> figure and one of the <a href=\"/wiki/Eight_Immortals\" title=\"Eight Immortals\">Eight Immortals</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/Taoism\" title=\"Taoism\">Taoist</a> pantheon. He is sometimes described as irascible and ill-tempered, but also benevolent to the poor, sick and the needy, whose suffering he alleviates with special medicine from his <a href=\"/wiki/Calabash\" title=\"Calabash\">gourd</a>. He is often portrayed as an ugly old man with dirty face, scraggy beard, and messy hair held by a golden band. He walks with the aid of an iron crutch and often has a gourd slung over his shoulder or held in his hand.<sup id=\"cite_ref-britannica_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-britannica-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> He often is depicted as a clown figure who descends to earth in the form of a beggar who uses his power to fight for the oppressed and needy.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The legend says that Li was born in the <a href=\"/wiki/Yuan_dynasty\" title=\"Yuan dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</a> (1279\u20131368),<sup id=\"cite_ref-wilkinson_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-wilkinson-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> and was originally named \"Li Yuan\". However, in folklore, he is depicted as <a href=\"/wiki/Laozi\" title=\"Laozi\">Laozi</a>'s apprentice, hence he should have lived in the sixth century BC.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Apotheosis\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Apotheosis</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Religious_influence\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Religious influence</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Iconography\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Iconography</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Modern_depictions\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Modern depictions</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Apotheosis\">Apotheosis</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Li_Tieguai&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Apotheosis\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Li_Tieguai,_by_Huang_Shen,_1757.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/87/Li_Tieguai%2C_by_Huang_Shen%2C_1757.jpg/220px-Li_Tieguai%2C_by_Huang_Shen%2C_1757.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"471\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/87/Li_Tieguai%2C_by_Huang_Shen%2C_1757.jpg/330px-Li_Tieguai%2C_by_Huang_Shen%2C_1757.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/87/Li_Tieguai%2C_by_Huang_Shen%2C_1757.jpg/440px-Li_Tieguai%2C_by_Huang_Shen%2C_1757.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"800\" data-file-height=\"1711\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Li_Tieguai,_by_Huang_Shen,_1757.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Huang Shen's painting of Li Tieguai, 1757</div></div></div>\n<p>The <a href=\"/wiki/Eight_Immortals\" title=\"Eight Immortals\">Eight Immortals</a> became immortals by means of practising Taoist magical arts. According to the myth, they lived on an island paradise, <a href=\"/wiki/Mount_Penglai\" title=\"Mount Penglai\">Mount Penglai</a> in eastern China, which only they could traverse due to the \"weak water\" which would not support ships. Among the Eight Immortals, Li Tieguai was one of the more popular, and was depicted as a man leaning on a crutch and holding a gourd. Some say that in the myth the \"gourd had spirals of smoke ascend from it, denoting his power of setting his spirit free from his body.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-wilson_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-wilson-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Others say that the gourd was full of medicine which he dispensed to the poor and needy.<sup id=\"cite_ref-britannica_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-britannica-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Li studied with <a href=\"/wiki/Laozi\" title=\"Laozi\">Laozi</a>, the founder of Taoism. He is said to have renounced material comforts and led a life of self-discipline as an act of religious devotion for 40 years, often going without food or sleep.<sup id=\"cite_ref-britannica_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-britannica-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Li lived in a cave in the early stage of his Taoist training. Laozi tempted him with a beautiful woman he had made of wood. After refusing to acknowledge the presence of this woman and therefore defeating his temptation, Laozi told him of his trick and rewarded him with a small white tablet. After consuming this tablet, Li was never hungry nor ill.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> Laozi tempted Li again with money. Some robbers had buried money in Li's field without knowing he was watching. Laozi approached him in disguise and told him he should take any money that came to him. After Li refused, saying that he did not care if he remained poor his whole life, Laozi rewarded him with another pill. This pill bestowed upon Li the ability to fly at amazing speeds.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Album_of_18_Daoist_Paintings_-_11.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c7/Album_of_18_Daoist_Paintings_-_11.jpg/220px-Album_of_18_Daoist_Paintings_-_11.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"114\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c7/Album_of_18_Daoist_Paintings_-_11.jpg/330px-Album_of_18_Daoist_Paintings_-_11.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c7/Album_of_18_Daoist_Paintings_-_11.jpg/440px-Album_of_18_Daoist_Paintings_-_11.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"4000\" data-file-height=\"2081\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Album_of_18_Daoist_Paintings_-_11.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><a href=\"/wiki/Zhang_Lu_(painter)\" title=\"Zhang Lu (painter)\">Zhang Lu</a>'s painting of Li Tieguai, early 16th century</div></div></div>\n<p>Before becoming an immortal, it was previously stated that Li was a very handsome man. However, on one occasion, his spirit travelled to Heaven to meet other immortals. He had told his apprentice, Li Qing, to wait for seven days for his spirit to return. If he did not return by then, Li Qing was to burn the body because that meant that he had become an immortal; but after six and a half days Li Qing had to go home to see to his sick mother one last time before she died. Li Qing thus cremated Li Tieguai's body. He passed by a dying beggar on his way to his mother's but did not have time to bury him.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> Upon returning, Li Tieguai's spirit found that his body had been cremated and had to enter the only body available at the time, the corpse of the homeless beggar who had just died of starvation. The beggar, unfortunately, had a long and pointed head, large ears with one large brass earring, a woolly and dishevelled beard and hair. He also had long, scraggy, and dark eyebrows, dark eyes, and he had a pan lid on his head and a lame leg. Laozi appeared and gave him a medicine gourd that could cure any illness and never emptied. Li then brought his apprentice's mother back to life using the liquid from his gourd. Li Qing was then dismissed as his apprentice, after being given a small pill and being told that he would work hard enough to become an immortal himself. This turned out to be true.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>\"The gourd served as a bedroom for the night and held medicine, which Li dispensed with great beneficence to the poor and needy.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-britannica_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-britannica-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Laozi also used the bottle to make him an iron crutch that would never rust nor break.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> He then told Li that he was ready to join the immortals. From then on, Li was tasked with curing the sick and he travelled to many lands and \"could be found wherever the sick lay dying or the poor were persecuted.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-ho26_10-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ho26-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Religious_influence\">Religious influence</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Li_Tieguai&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Religious influence\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Wang_Zhao%27s_painting_of_Li_Tieguai.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Wang_Zhao%27s_painting_of_Li_Tieguai.jpg/220px-Wang_Zhao%27s_painting_of_Li_Tieguai.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"471\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Wang_Zhao%27s_painting_of_Li_Tieguai.jpg/330px-Wang_Zhao%27s_painting_of_Li_Tieguai.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Wang_Zhao%27s_painting_of_Li_Tieguai.jpg/440px-Wang_Zhao%27s_painting_of_Li_Tieguai.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1870\" data-file-height=\"4000\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Wang_Zhao%27s_painting_of_Li_Tieguai.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Wang Zhao's painting of Li Tieguai, Ming dynasty</div></div></div>\n<p>Probably the second most popular of the Eight Immortals, Li is associated with medicine. His symbol of an iron crutch still hangs outside some traditional apothecaries. One of the reasons for him not being extremely popular is due to his \"renowned bad temper and eccentricities.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-ho26_10-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ho26-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> Sometimes, the non devout seek out prescriptions from him through certain Taoist priests. His magical, medical gourd is his more popular sign which is favoured by professional exorcists. As a beggar, he uses his form to \"fight for the rights of the poor and those in need.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-ho26_10-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ho26-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> \"He is very much a clown figure and his popularity rests upon the twin attractions of being seen as one of the downtrodden, who is really more powerful than the strongest, and the clown who is irascible.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-ho26_10-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ho26-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The Eight Immortals are examples of how all can obtain immortality. Most of the immortals (including Li) were common folk who attracted the attention of the gods through suffering unjust treatment, without complaint, and gave more to others than themselves. They were admitted to eternal life as a reward for their acts on earth and bearing gifts to the <a href=\"/wiki/Old_Man_of_the_South_Pole\" title=\"Old Man of the South Pole\">Old Man of the South Pole</a>, the god of longevity.<sup id=\"cite_ref-christy_11-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-christy-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> \"The path to immortality includes achieving physical and spiritual harmony through meditation, diet, exercise, breath control, and the use of herbs. To achieve this state, one also had to eliminate all disease and evil from the body and spirit\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-wilkinson_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-wilkinson-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Iconography\">Iconography</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Li_Tieguai&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Iconography\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>His characteristic emblems are the gourd bottle which identifies him as one of the Eight Immortals and also his iron crutch. A vapour cloud emanates from the gourd, and within it is the sage's <i>hun</i> (<a href=\"/wiki/Soul_(spirit)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Soul (spirit)\">soul</a>); which may be depicted as a formless shape or as a miniature double of his bodily self.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Modern_depictions\">Modern depictions</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Li_Tieguai&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Modern depictions\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In the television show <i><a href=\"/wiki/Jackie_Chan_Adventures\" title=\"Jackie Chan Adventures\">Jackie Chan Adventures</a></i>, Li was shown to be the Immortal who sealed away <a href=\"/wiki/List_of_Jackie_Chan_Adventures_characters#Bai_Tza\" title=\"List of Jackie Chan Adventures characters\">Bai Tza, The Water Demon</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Li_Tieguai&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/File:Commons-logo.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/12px-Commons-logo.svg.png\" width=\"12\" height=\"16\" class=\"noviewer\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/18px-Commons-logo.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/24px-Commons-logo.svg.png 2x\" data-fi